## 1. Logging in .NET Class Libraries: Best Practices

** Dont use `Console.WriteLine` or fixed log files in a library.** Writing directly to console or a file from within SDK code is **not appropriate** for reusable libraries, as it hijacks the applications output and offers no way for library users to control it. Instead, **use logging abstractions** so consumers can configure if, where, and how logs are recorded. By avoiding direct console calls, you prevent unexpected console spam in GUI apps or services and let the app developer decide on logging. [\[stackoverflow.com\]](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2764384/logging-in-a-c-sharp-library)

** Do use `Microsoft.Extensions.Logging` abstractions** (the `ILogger` interface and related types) to emit logs from your SDK. This is the modern .NET approach for libraries and offers flexibility and compatibility. By accepting an `ILogger` (or `ILoggerFactory`) in your SDKs APIs, you allow the application to route logs through its chosen logging framework (whether thats console, file, UI, Application Insights, etc.) without your SDK needing to know the details. Many popular .NET libraries (Entity Framework Core, ASP.NET Core, etc.) follow this pattern, integrating with `ILogger` so that all logs funnel through a unified system. [\[stackoverflow.com\]](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2764384/logging-in-a-c-sharp-library), [\[stackoverflow.com\]](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2764384/logging-in-a-c-sharp-library)

**ILogger vs ILoggerFactory:** If your SDK has multiple internal components that each should log under a different category (usually the category is the class name), its often best to accept an `ILoggerFactory` and use it to create loggers for each class. For example, a USB SDK might have separate log categories for DeviceDiscovery and DeviceConnection classes. Passing an `ILoggerFactory` once (e.g., into your main class or via dependency injection) lets you create distinct `ILogger<T>` instances for each class. On the other hand, if a single `ILogger` instance is sufficient (e.g., your SDK is small or you only need one category), you can accept an `ILogger<T>` for the main class directly. The official guidance is: use `ILoggerFactory` for library entry points that may spawn other helper classes, and use `ILogger<T>` for cases where the logger is only used in one class. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/extensions/logging-library-authors), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/extensions/logging-library-authors) [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/extensions/logging-library-authors)

**No-op Defaults:** Provide a sensible default if the caller does not supply a logger. *Silent by default* is usually the right approach for libraries. In practice, this means you can allow an `ILogger` or `ILoggerFactory` parameter to be optional (nullable) and, if not provided, use a no-op logger. The .NET `Microsoft.Extensions.Logging.Abstractions` package offers `NullLogger` and `NullLoggerFactory`singletons that implement `ILogger`/`ILoggerFactory` but simply discard all messages. For example, your SDKs constructor can do: [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/extensions/logging-library-authors), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/extensions/logging-library-authors)

```csharp
public MyUsbSdk(ILoggerFactory? loggerFactory = null) {
    ILoggerFactory factory = loggerFactory ?? NullLoggerFactory.Instance;
    _logger = factory.CreateLogger<MyUsbSdk>();
}
```

This way, if the user doesnt care about logs, they dont have to do anything (no output will occur). But if they want logs, they pass in a configured logger factory or logger. This follows the guideline of using *no-op logging defaults* to avoid forcing consumers to always specify a logger. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/extensions/logging-library-authors)

**Avoid forcing a specific framework:** Do not tie your library to a particular logging **implementation** like log4net, NLog, or Serilog  and definitely do not *internally initialize* such loggers. Instead, depend only on the `Microsoft.Extensions.Logging` **abstraction**. This keeps your SDK flexible and avoids forcing extra dependencies on users. Advanced users can still integrate third-party loggers by plugging them into the `ILogger` pipeline (for instance, an `ILogger` can be backed by Serilog or NLog providers, as shown in the Stack Overflow example). Your library should remain agnostic to the logging backend. [\[stackoverflow.com\]](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2764384/logging-in-a-c-sharp-library)

**Structured Logging:** Embrace structured logging practices to make logs more machine-readable and searchable. In .NETs logging API, this means using **message templates** with named placeholders instead of string concatenation or interpolation. For example, do:

```csharp
_logger.LogInformation("Discovered device {@DeviceId} at port {Port}", device.Id, portName);
```

rather than: `_logger.LogInformation("Discovered device " + device.Id + " at port " + portName);`. The template `"{Port}"` and `"{@DeviceId}"` will capture those values as structured fields. This is more performant (the template is not rendered if the log level is disabled) and helps downstream log processors filter by fields. **Do not** use string interpolation `$"..."` in logging calls  that would format the string eagerly even if the log level is off, hurting performance. The official guidance is to avoid interpolation for logging and rely on the loggers formatting features. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/extensions/logging-library-authors), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/extensions/logging-library-authors) [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/extensions/logging-library-authors)

**Source-Generated Logging (High-performance):** In .NET 6+ you can use the **LoggerMessage** attribute to have the compiler source-generate high-performance logging methods. This is an advanced but highly efficient technique especially useful in libraries where overhead must be minimal. The source generator creates static methods that are strongly-typed, use no boxing or unnecessary allocations, and skip formatting if disabled. For example, you might define: [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/extensions/logging-library-authors), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/extensions/logging-library-authors)

```csharp
static partial class Log {
    [LoggerMessage(EventId = 1, Level = LogLevel.Debug, Message = "Polled USB port {Port}  {DeviceCount} devices found")]
    public static partial void PortScanResult(this ILogger logger, string Port, int DeviceCount);
}
```

After building, you can call `_logger.PortScanResult(portName, count);` and benefit from auto-generated efficient code. Source-generated logging isnt mandatory, but its recommended for library authors to improve performance and maintain consistency (especially if your SDK logs frequently). Whether you use it or not, always consider performance of logging in library code (more on this in section 3). [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/extensions/logging-library-authors), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/extensions/logging-library-authors)

**Log Levels and Usage:** Utilize log levels appropriately:

*   **Debug/Trace**  for very detailed diagnostic information (e.g. USB raw data bytes, enter/exit of methods, etc.). These are usually off in production.
*   **Information**  for high-level events that are part of normal operation (e.g. Device connected, Device discovery completed, 3 devices found). In a library, you might use Info sparingly to note significant state changes.
*   **Warning**  for abnormal or unexpected conditions that are not fatal (e.g. Retrying read after transient error, or Device responded with an error, will attempt recovery).
*   **Error**  for errors that prevent an operation from succeeding (e.g. Failed to initialize device before throwing an exception).
*   **Critical**  rarely used in libraries; indicates a serious failure likely affecting the entire app (e.g. out-of-memory or data corruption).

Design your logging such that in typical usage, an application can run at **Information** level and see important lifecycle events of your SDK (if they enable that level), while Debug/Trace can be turned on to diagnose issues in depth. Keep the default behavior quiet (e.g., an app that doesnt enable your logs sees nothing, unless something goes terribly wrong and perhaps an exception is thrown). Also consider categorizing or **tagging** logs with event IDs or categories for filtering. For example, define event IDs for groups of events (Microsoft.Extensions.Logging allows an `EventId` in log calls). This can help consumers filter only device discovery logs vs only data transfer logs if you set it up. In practice, using separate `ILogger` categories (one per class or subsystem) often suffices since users can filter by namespace or class name.

**Example  Integrating ILogger in a Library:** Below is a simplified example of how your USB SDK might expose and use logging:

```csharp
public class UsbDeviceFinder {
    private readonly ILogger<UsbDeviceFinder> _logger;

    public UsbDeviceFinder(ILoggerFactory? loggerFactory = null) {
        ILoggerFactory lf = loggerFactory ?? NullLoggerFactory.Instance;
        _logger = lf.CreateLogger<UsbDeviceFinder>();
    }

    public IList<DeviceInfo> DiscoverDevices() {
        _logger.LogInformation("Starting device discovery..."); 
        var devices = new List<DeviceInfo>();
        foreach(string port in GetCandidatePorts()) {
            _logger.LogDebug("Probing port {Port}", port);
            try {
                var device = TryConnect(port);
                if(device != null) {
                    devices.Add(device);
                    _logger.LogInformation("Device <{Device}> found on {Port}", device.Name, port);
                }
            } catch(Exception ex) {
                _logger.LogWarning(ex, "Error probing port {Port}", port);
            }
        }
        _logger.LogInformation("Discovery complete. {Count} devices found.", devices.Count);
        return devices;
    }
}
```

In this code:

*   The constructor accepts an optional `ILoggerFactory` and uses `NullLoggerFactory` if none is provided, ensuring no NullReference and no logging if unused.
*   Logging calls use `LogInformation`, `LogDebug`, `LogWarning` with structured messages. Critical information (start/end of discovery, and device found) is Info level, detailed steps (each port) is Debug, and exceptions during probing are logged at Warning with the exception attached (this writes exception details to the log for troubleshooting).
*   No `Console.WriteLine` appears  the library doesnt dictate where the log goes. If the app passes in a logger factory configured with, say, a Console logger at Info level, they will see Starting device discovery, Device X found, etc., but not the debug-level messages (unless they enable Debug). If they pass nothing, all `_logger.Log...` calls are no-ops.

**Structured context**: Note the use of placeholders like `{Port}` and `{Device}`  this ensures those values are available to the logging system as separate fields (and not formatted if the log level is off). Also, `LogWarning(ex, "Error probing port {Port}")` will include the exception stack trace in the log. This is more useful than just throwing immediately, as it allows capturing non-fatal errors (e.g., a port in use) for later analysis without stopping the entire discovery process.

## 2. Event Tracing for Windows (ETW) and `EventSource` in SDKs

**What is ETW/EventSource?** In .NET, **EventSource** is a special logging mechanism for high-performance **tracing** events, often tied to Event Tracing for Windows. An `EventSource` is a class you define that emits structured events (with event IDs, levels, and payloads), which can be listened to by ETW listeners (on Windows) or the cross-platform EventPipe mechanism. ETW/EventSource is typically used for **telemetry** and diagnostic events that tools or advanced users can subscribe to, often out-of-process. Crucially, EventSource has extremely low overhead when no listener is attached  essentially near-zero cost for disabled events. This makes it ideal for logging in **tight loops or high-frequency** scenarios (where even an `ILogger` might add measurable overhead). [\[aloneguid.uk\]](https://www.aloneguid.uk/posts/2022/09/tracing-vs-logging-performance-net6/)

**When should an SDK use EventSource?** Consider EventSource (ETW) in your SDK if:

*   You have **very high-volume debug information** that should not always be on, but you want to make available for deep diagnostics. Examples: per-packet or per-byte trace in a network/serial library, performance telemetry (like timings of operations), or frequent state changes. You can instrument these via EventSource and know that if no one is listening, the impact is minimal (a few nanoseconds per call). [\[aloneguid.uk\]](https://www.aloneguid.uk/posts/2022/09/tracing-vs-logging-performance-net6/)
*   You want to enable **system-level diagnostics** where an external tool (like PerfView, Event Viewer, or dotnet-trace) can catch your librarys events even if the application didnt explicitly configure logging. EventSource events can be captured outside of the process (on Windows, via ETW sessions). For example, if a user of your USB SDK is having a problem, they could run a PerfView capture that includes your EventSource events to diagnose, without the app needing to have logging code.
*   You need to integrate with Windows performance counters or EventLog. ETW is a common path for that.

On the other hand, if your logging needs are modest and mostly for the app developers benefit, a pure ILogger approach suffices. EventSource is an advanced option typically used in **base libraries and Microsofts own SDKs** for low-level tracing.

**Examples of ETW usage in .NET libraries:** The Azure SDK for .NET is a prime example  it uses EventSource under the hood for logging. Azure SDK client libraries emit trace events for each HTTP request/response and other internal operations via EventSource, providing *minimal overhead logging* when not enabled. Consumers who want those logs can use provided helpers to turn them on. .NET runtime and core libraries also use EventSource internally (for example, System.Net has a `NetEventSource` for networking traces, and various BCL components use EventSource for verbose logging). [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/azure/sdk/logging)

**Pros and Cons  EventSource vs. ILogger:**

| Aspect                     | **ILogger (Microsoft.Extensions.Logging)**                                                                                                                                                                                                       | **EventSource (ETW tracing)**                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        |
| -------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| *Ease of use*              | Very easy for app developers  plug into existing logging (Console, files, etc.) via providers. Simple API for library (LogInformation, etc.).                                                                                                   | Requires defining an EventSource class and possibly EventListeners. More setup for consumers (need to enable via listeners or OS tools).                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             |
| *Overhead (when disabled)* | Low, but not zero. Even with no listeners, an `ILogger.LogInformation` call incurs some method calls (tens of nanoseconds and small allocation) [\[aloneguid.uk\]](https://www.aloneguid.uk/posts/2022/09/tracing-vs-logging-performance-net6/). | **Ultra-low**. If no listener is attached, EventSource writes are essentially a no-op at the native level (a few nanoseconds, no allocation) [\[aloneguid.uk\]](https://www.aloneguid.uk/posts/2022/09/tracing-vs-logging-performance-net6/). Optimized for high-frequency events.                                                                                                                                   |
| *Structured data*          | Supports structured data (via message templates or attaching objects/state). Good for both human and machine reading.                                                                                                                            | Supports structured payloads (you define typed fields in the event). Excellent for machine processing and performance tooling. Not as straightforward to log arbitrary complex objects (must serialize to fields).                                                                                                                                                                                                   |
| *Log Levels / Filtering*   | Built-in levels (Trace, Debug, Info, etc.) and category filtering. Can configure per category in app config.                                                                                                                                     | Supports levels (Verbose, Informational, Warning, Error, Critical) and keywords for fine-grained enabling. Filtering is typically done by enabling/disabling specific event IDs or levels via the listening tool.                                                                                                                                                                                                    |
| *Consumer Experience*      | **In-process**: logs go to whatever sinks the app set up (console, file, telemetry, etc.). Easy to see during development (just open console or log file).                                                                                       | **Out-of-process capable**: can be captured by PerfView, Event Viewer, or via `EventListener` in code. Not visible unless explicitly turned on, which might be done by advanced users or tools.                                                                                                                                                                                                                      |
| *Cross-platform*           | Fully cross-platform (Microsoft.Extensions.Logging works on Windows, Linux, etc. with appropriate providers).                                                                                                                                    | Mostly cross-platform. ETW as such is Windows-specific, but .NET Cores EventSource works with EventPipe on Linux, and you can use `EventListener` in code on any platform.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          |
| *Integration*              | Out-of-the-box integration with ASP.NET Core, generic host, and third-party frameworks (Serilog, etc.)  its the standard .NET logging model.                                                                                                   | Can integrate with `ILogger` via a bridging provider (e.g., `EventSourceLoggerProvider`) or by writing an EventListener that feeds ILogger. Azure SDK provides `AzureEventSourceListener` to route EventSource events to other outputs [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/azure/sdk/logging), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/azure/sdk/logging). |
| *Features*                 | Supports scopes, event IDs, and can be extended via custom `ILoggerProvider`s. Rich ecosystem.                                                                                                                                                   | Supports advanced features like **activities** (correlation IDs), **keywords** (to categorize events), and is tied into System.Diagnostics tracing (can work with `EventCounter`, etc.). Good for performance counters and telemetry events.                                                                                                                                                                         |

In summary, **ILogger is usually the default choice** for library logging due to its simplicity and compatibility, but **EventSource is valuable for high-performance and advanced diagnostics**. Its not necessarily an either/or choice  you can use both: For example, your SDK could primarily use ILogger for normal logs, but also define an EventSource for very detailed trace events. Or, you could use EventSource internally and provide an adapter so that if the app wants, it can pipe those events into ILogger. (Azure SDK does something like this  they have an `AzureEventSourceListener` class that can forward Azure SDK EventSource events to an `ILogger` or to the console). [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/azure/sdk/logging), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/azure/sdk/logging)

**Implementing EventSource in your SDK:** To use EventSource, you create a class deriving `System.Diagnostics.Tracing.EventSource`. Define events with the `[Event]` attribute. Example skeleton:

```csharp
[EventSource(Name = "Contoso-UsbSdk")]
public sealed class UsbSdkEventSource : EventSource
{
    public static UsbSdkEventSource Log = new UsbSdkEventSource();
    private UsbSdkEventSource() {}

    // Define events:
    [Event(1, Level = EventLevel.Informational, Message = "USB device {0} connected on {1}")]
    public void DeviceConnected(string deviceId, string port) => WriteEvent(1, deviceId, port);

    [Event(2, Level = EventLevel.Verbose, Message = "Received {0} bytes: {1}")]
    public void DataReceived(int byteCount, string dataHex) => WriteEvent(2, byteCount, dataHex);

    [Event(3, Level = EventLevel.Error, Message = "Error: {0}")]
    public void UsbError(string errorMessage) => WriteEvent(3, errorMessage);
}
```

Internally, youd use it like: `UsbSdkEventSource.Log.DeviceConnected(id, port);`. By default, these calls do nothing (unless a listener is active). To capture them, a developer could use an `EventListener` in code, or (on Windows) use an ETW trace session. However, you might also make it easier by providing an opt-in switch. For instance, you could expose a method to enable console logging of EventSource events (similar to Azures `AzureEventSourceListener.CreateConsoleLogger()` which registers a listener printing to console). This way, if someone using your SDK wants to troubleshoot, they could call something like `UsbSdkEventSource.Log.EnableConsoleLogging()` during development to see all the trace events. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/azure/sdk/logging), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/azure/sdk/logging)

**ETW vs ILogger performance note:** As mentioned, if performance is critical (say your SDK reads hundreds of USB packets per second), an EventSource can log each packet with virtually no cost when logging is off. By contrast, an ILogger call, even if nothing is listening, has to go through the logging pipeline (which, while highly optimized, may allocate a little and do some work  in .NET 6 tests, a no-op ILogger call was \~40 ns vs \~3.5 ns for EventSource). This difference can add up in extremely tight loops. So for *hot path* instrumentation, EventSource is preferable. You can still keep an ILogger for higher-level messages. [\[aloneguid.uk\]](https://www.aloneguid.uk/posts/2022/09/tracing-vs-logging-performance-net6/)

**When not to use EventSource:** If your librarys logging needs are fully met by ILogger and you dont have a scenario for trace tooling or ultra-low overhead, you might skip EventSource to avoid extra complexity. Also, ETW is less relevant if your library will be used in non-Windows environments that wont run event listeners (though as noted, .NET's EventSource works cross-platform via EventPipe).

## 3. Alternative Logging Designs and Patterns

Beyond the basic `ILogger` vs `EventSource` choice, consider these additional patterns and mechanisms for logging in an SDK:

*   **Custom .NET Events vs Logging:** Some libraries expose .NET events (the C# event/delegate kind) to notify of certain conditions. For example, a `SerialPort` class might raise an `DataReceived` event. Such events are part of the librarys API and allow the **application to react in real-time**. However, they are not a replacement for logging; theyre more for functional callbacks. Use events to expose important milestones or data streams (if appropriate to your design), but for general diagnostics and errors, prefer logging or exceptions. In EF Core, for instance, there is a concept of *diagnostic events* that can be subscribed to, but even their documentation notes **diagnostic listeners are not designed for logging... Microsoft.Extensions.Logging is a better choice for logging**. So, generally, only introduce custom events if the consumer might need to programmatically react, not just to record information. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/ef/core/logging-events-diagnostics/), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/ef/core/logging-events-diagnostics/)

*   **Dependency Injection (DI) Patterns:** If your SDK is meant to be used in apps that support DI (like ASP.NET Core or any app using the generic Host builder), design your classes to take `ILogger<T>` or `ILoggerFactory` in their constructors. Mark these parameters as optional or have overloads so that non-DI scenarios can still instantiate your classes easily. In a DI scenario, the container will supply the logger automatically. For example, in an ASP.NET Core app, if you add your SDKs services to the service container, the ILogger will get injected because the framework knows how to provide ILogger<T>. This means a user can do `services.AddSingleton<UsbDeviceFinder>();` and if your `UsbDeviceFinder` has a constructor with `ILogger<UsbDeviceFinder>`, it just works. If DI is not in use, you still allow passing a logger or falling back to none. This pattern keeps your logging usage flexible. (Under the hood, in DI scenarios the `ILoggerFactory` is itself registered as a service, so it can provide the logger.)

*   **Optional Logger (Nullable Patterns):** We touched on this with NullLogger. The idea is to *not force* the consumer to always provide a logger. Provide overloads or default parameters. One pattern is:
    ```csharp
    public UsbDeviceFinder(ILogger<UsbDeviceFinder>? logger = null) {
        _logger = logger ?? NullLogger<UsbDeviceFinder>.Instance;
    }
    ```
    This way you directly accept `ILogger<T>` but make it optional by allowing null (and substituting a no-op). Choose what fits your API style  some prefer to accept `ILoggerFactory` to be future-proof (since it can spawn multiple category loggers internally). In either case, **document** that by default the logging is disabled unless the caller wires it up. This null = silent approach is explicitly recommended in .NET library guidelines. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/extensions/logging-library-authors), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/extensions/logging-library-authors)

*   **Silent by default vs. configurable verbosity:** The default stance is that libraries should be silent unless asked to speak. This avoids cluttering logs unexpectedly. However, you can provide *knobs* for verbosity. For instance, an environment variable or static setting that, if set, makes the library emit debug logs to console for quick troubleshooting. (The .NET runtime itself does this for certain components; e.g., setting `System.Net.Http.EnableDebugLogging` environment variable at runtime will cause System.Net to dump logs to console). In your USB SDK, you might not need such complexity if using ILogger (since the app can just set log level to Debug). But if you want, say, an emergency way to get logs even if the app hasnt configured ILogger, a fallback environment-based trigger could be an idea (with caution). In general, rely on the logging framework configuration rather than custom flags, except perhaps for extremely low-level libraries. For example, if your SDK internally uses EventSource, an advanced user could enable those traces via standard tools  no custom flag needed.

*   **Log filtering and categories:** Make sure to choose clear categories (usually the full namespace + class name via `ILogger<T>` does this automatically). Consumers can filter by category string to reduce noise. Provide guidance in your docs/readme like Enable logging for category `Contoso.UsbSdk.*` to see SDK logs. If using EventSource, use the `EventSource.Name` (e.g., `Contoso-UsbSdk`) as the provider name that users will enable. Also consider grouping event IDs or using `EventKeywords` in EventSource if you have different kinds of events (e.g., a keyword for data transfer vs another for connection events)  this allows listeners to toggle categories of events.

*   **Conditional compilation for logs:** In rare cases, you might include extremely verbose logging that you **only** want in debug builds of your library (and completely omitted in release builds). For example, dumping the entire data stream might be something you dont even want accidentally enabled in production for performance or security reasons. You can use `#if DEBUG` or the `[Conditional("DEBUG")]` attribute on logging methods to include/exclude these. This is the same idea behind `Debug.WriteLine` (which only runs in Debug builds). Use this sparingly  typically for internal dev debugging rather than as a feature for consumers. If something is potentially useful to an end-user in diagnosing issues, its better to make it a runtime-controlled log (so they can enable it in production if needed) rather than a compile-time disabled one. So, you might use `Debug.Assert` or `Debug.WriteLine` for sanity checks during development of the SDK, but anything that might help an end-user should be behind a log level check instead (so it can be turned on via configuration, not by recompiling the library).

*   **OpenTelemetry and distributed tracing:** Since the prompt mentioned telemetry, its worth noting modern .NET libraries can also integrate with OpenTelemetry for standardized tracing/metrics. For a USB SDK, this might be less relevant (telemetry is more common in web services or distributed systems), but if needed, you could expose OpenTelemetry **Activity** traces for operations. However, this is an advanced topic; generally focus on logging and perhaps add tracing later if needed.

**Bottom line:** Design your logging so that it is **pluggable, optional, and doesnt degrade performance** when unused. Whether through `ILogger` or `EventSource (ETW)`, ensure the consumer has full control over what logging is collected. Log messages should be concise, informative, and avoid flooding the log with low-value data in normal operation.

## 4. Error Reporting Strategies in an SDK

Logging and telemetry are only one side of the diagnostics coin. The other is **error handling**: how your SDK signals failures to the caller. Here are best practices for exceptions and error reporting in a .NET library:

**Use Exceptions to Signal Errors:** In .NET, exceptions are the standard way to indicate an operation could not be completed. Your SDK should throw exceptions for error conditions that the calling code either *should* handle or at least be made aware of. For example, if no USB device is found during discovery when one was expected, or if a read from the device times out in a method that was supposed to return data, that method should throw an exception. Do **not** rely on logging alone to report an error  logs may never be seen by the consumer. An exception forces the issue to be acknowledged (via try/catch or it will crash the app). A **crashed app with an exception is preferable over a silent failure** with just a log message, because it makes the problem obvious and diagnosable. [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/standard/exceptions/best-practices-for-exceptions)

**Which Exception Type?** You have two main choices: use a relevant **built-in exception** or define a **custom exception class** for your SDK. The general guideline:

*   If a suitable standard exception exists that accurately describes the problem, you can use it. For instance, `ArgumentException` (or `ArgumentNullException) for bad arguments, `InvalidOperationException`for method calls at inappropriate times (e.g., calling a function on a device that isnt connected),`TimeoutException`for an operation that timed out,`IOException`or`UnauthorizedAccessException\` for low-level I/O errors coming from the OS, etc.
*   If the error is very domain-specific or needs to carry extra information, consider a custom exception. A custom exception provides a clear, strongly-typed way for callers to catch errors specific to your library. For example, you might define `DeviceNotFoundException`, or `ConnectionFailedException`, or `ProtocolErrorException` for various failure cases in the USB communication domain. By deriving from `System.Exception` (or a subclass like IOException if appropriate), you integrate with .NET exception handling while adding context. (Do not derive from `ApplicationException`  that is outdated guidance; simply subclass Exception or a logical subclass). [\[stackoverflow.com\]](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/4791823/what-are-industry-standard-best-practices-for-implementing-custom-exceptions-in), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/standard/design-guidelines/using-standard-exception-types)

Often, a mix is good: use built-in exceptions for common scenarios (so developers immediately recognize, say, an ArgumentOutOfRangeException without learning a new type), but use custom ones for the unique error conditions of your SDK. For instance, if the SDK is asked to open a specific device by ID and its not present, throwing a `DeviceNotFoundException` (perhaps subclassing KeyNotFoundException or IOException) could be clearer than just an InvalidOperationException.

**Custom Exception Best Practices:** If you create custom exceptions, follow .NET conventions:

*   Name them with the suffix Exception.
*   Derive from Exception (or a subclass if it makes sense logically).
*   Make them `[Serializable]` and implement the standard exception constructors (the default, one that takes a string message, and one that takes string + inner Exception). This ensures they work well if the exception crosses AppDomain boundaries or is rethrown.
*   Optionally add extra properties to convey additional info. For example, a `ConnectionFailedException` might have a property for the `PortName` or `DeviceId` it was trying to connect to. This can aid in debugging (and can be included in the exception `Message` as well). [\[stackoverflow.com\]](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/4791823/what-are-industry-standard-best-practices-for-implementing-custom-exceptions-in), [\[stackoverflow.com\]](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/4791823/what-are-industry-standard-best-practices-for-implementing-custom-exceptions-in)
*   Ensure the `Message` property of the exception (which you pass via the constructor) is clear and includes useful details. E.g., `"Connection to device 1234 failed: access denied"` rather than just `"Connection failed."`.

**When to throw vs. when to log and suppress:** As a rule, **if an error prevents the operation from fulfilling its contract, throw an exception**. Do not catch an internal exception and merely log it, then continue as if nothing happened  that could lead to incorrect results or undefined behavior in the caller. For example, if reading from the USB device throws an IOException (maybe the device was unplugged), your SDK method should probably let that exception propagate (or wrap it in a higher-level exception with more context) rather than eating it and returning, say, an empty result. Eating exceptions makes issues hard to discover. The only time you might handle internally is if you have a valid *retry or fallback* strategy: e.g., catch a transient error, log it (at debug or info), and retry the operation a couple times, then ultimately throw if it keeps failing.

**Log **and** throw:** Its acceptable (and often helpful) to log an error at the point you detect it **and** then throw an exception for the caller. The log (especially at an error or warning level) provides context in application logs about what happened right before the exception was thrown. Meanwhile, the exception travels up to be handled by the app. Be careful not to log the same error too many times though  typically log it once at the origin. For example:

```csharp
if (!deviceFound) {
    _logger.LogError("Device with ID {DeviceId} not found on any port.", id);
    throw new DeviceNotFoundException(id);
}
```

This way, if the user has logging enabled, they see an explicit error message in logs. If they dont, the exception still surfaces the issue. Logging an error and throwing an exception are not redundant if done thoughtfully  the log can have more diagnostic detail (maybe a stack trace, or context like after 3 retries) whereas the exception carries the information up the stack in a programmatically catchable way.

**Exception categories (transient vs permanent):** Its useful to design your exceptions (or document them) in terms of which might be *transient* (temporary, might succeed if retried) vs *permanent* (will fail no matter how many retries until something external changes). For instance, a **timeout** or **temporary OS error** could be considered transient  the user might catch that and try again. A **configuration error** or **unsupported operation** is permanent until the code or environment is fixed. How to convey this?

*   Documentation: clearly note in XML comments which exceptions can be thrown and why. Mention if an exception is likely transient (e.g., This exception may indicate a temporary communication hiccup; the operation might succeed if retried.).
*   Exception types: You might have `TransientException` vs `PermanentException` base classes, but that is rarely done explicitly. More common is to use existing types (e.g., `IOException` often indicates an I/O issue that might be transient or not  up to caller to decide).
*   Exception properties: a custom exception could include a boolean `IsTransient` or an error code enum.
*   Microsofts libraries often simply document the conditions. For example, `SqlException` has a list of error numbers that are transient (like deadlocks). In your case, `DeviceBusyException` might be considered transient (maybe the user can try later), whereas `DeviceNotFoundException` is not going to succeed on retry unless the device is plugged in.

Given this is a relatively small SDK, you may not need an elaborate system. Just be mindful: if a particular error could naturally be resolved by retrying after a short wait, make sure the exception or log gives a hint. (E.g., a message Device is busy (error XYZ), try again later versus Device busy)

**Provide context in exceptions:** Always include enough information in the exception message (and properties) for someone to understand the error and potentially troubleshoot. If an operation fails, mention what it was doing: e.g., Timed out waiting for response to command GET\_STATUS (timeout 5000ms)  this is much better than Operation timed out. If you catch a lower-level exception to wrap in your custom exception, carry over the `InnerException`. For instance, if a SerialPort throws an IOException with OS error, wrap it in your `UsbTransferException` but include the original as InnerException so no information is lost. This way a developer can drill down to see the root cause.

**Dont overload logging with error handling logic:** Avoid using logs as the mechanism to communicate errors to the caller. (For example, dont have a function return, rely on the user to check logs to know it failed  thats very bad practice.) Logs are supplementary. The proper channel for errors is exceptions or error codes (in some patterns). .NET primarily uses exceptions for errors; only use error codes (e.g., return a bool or special result object) if exceptions would be too frequent (not the case in most scenarios; exceptions should be for exceptional conditions, not routine flow control).

**Consistent exception scheme:** Try to use a consistent set of exception types in your SDK. Perhaps all device-related errors throw a `UsbDeviceException` (from which more specific ones derive). This can allow a consumer to catch your general exception if they just want to handle any error from the USB SDK in one swoop. For example:

```csharp
try {
    sdk.SendCommand(...);
} catch (UsbDeviceException ex) {
    // handle any USB SDK related error
}
```

Where `UsbDeviceException` might be a base class for `DeviceNotFoundException`, `TimeoutException` (you could use the built-in TimeoutException or subclass UsbDeviceException into a UsbTimeoutException, etc.), `ProtocolException`, etc. This is a design choice  not strictly necessary, but it can improve the API usability.

**Surface errors immediately:** If an error is fatal to the operation, throw ASAP. Dont bury errors. For example, if during discovery, accessing a certain port throws an UnauthorizedAccessException (perhaps the user lacks permission), you have a design decision: do you stop the whole discovery and throw up, or just log and skip that port? This depends on what the method is supposed to do. If discovery is find all devices you can, it might make sense to catch permission exceptions on one port, log a warning, and continue trying others (so that you still return any devices found on other ports). Thats a reasonable approach  but you should at least somehow allow the user to know that one port couldnt be scanned. Logging a warning is good. Maybe also provide a summary in the return (like a list of errors encountered, or count of ports failed)  but that might complicate the API. Logging might suffice there, since it wasnt a total failure. Conversely, if an error means the whole operation results are suspect or unusable, then stop and throw.

In conclusion, **throw exceptions for errors** and use logging to record additional context around those exceptions. Use custom exceptions when they add value (clearer intent or additional info). Favor standard ones when applicable (so developers dont have to learn new exception types for common mistakes). By following .NET conventions, you make it easy for SDK consumers to catch and handle errors appropriately.

## 5. Special Considerations for USB/Serial Communication Logging

The context of a **USB communication SDK** brings some specific challenges and patterns for logging:

**Connection and State Changes:** Log the major state transitions of the device connections. For example, when a device is detected/connected, when it is disconnected or a communication session starts/ends. These are high-level events that are very useful to have in logs (often at **Information** level). E.g., USB device #1234 connected on COM3, Connection to device #1234 closed. If the SDK manages persistent connections, also log things like Retrying connection..., Device reset signaled etc., as appropriate. This helps trace the lifecycle of devices in the system.

**Communication Errors and Anomalies:** In serial communication, you may encounter checksum mismatches, malformed responses, timeouts, etc. These should generally be logged at **Warning or Error** level (depending on severity) *and* often correlate to exceptions. For instance, if a read times out, you might log a warning Read timed out waiting for response to command X and then throw a TimeoutException. If a protocol error occurs (got an unexpected byte sequence), you might log details for debugging (perhaps at Debug level if its not fatal, or Warning if it indicates a probable issue).

**Data Transmission Logs:** Be cautious with logging raw data transfers. In debugging serial protocols, its **invaluable** to see the bytes or messages exchanged. But those can be very frequent and voluminous. A strategy:

*   Provide **Debug/Trace level** logs for the data content. E.g., at Debug level, log  SEND: 0x10 0x25 0xFF 0x00 0xAA (5 bytes) and  RECV:  (bytes). These should be conditional on debug level to avoid overhead when not needed. You might even guard them with `if (_logger.IsEnabled(LogLevel.Debug))` checks around any heavy formatting (to avoid converting a byte array to hex string unnecessarily).
*   Possibly aggregate repetitive data logs. If you are streaming data at a high rate, logging every single packet might be overkill even in Debug. Maybe allow chunking or sample logging (every nth packet or every X seconds log a summary). This depends on use case.
*   Consider letting the user supply a callback for raw data logging if needed. For example, some libraries let users register an trace listener for received bytes. But that again overlaps with just using Logger. Alternatively, if using EventSource, you can emit events for data received/sent. Then a user can capture a trace if they really need the byte-level detail.

**Device Discovery Process:** The discovery process (scanning ports for devices) is something that likely should be logged at **Info/Debug** levels. Info level could say Starting discovery on COM1-COM8 or Found 2 candidate USB devices via PNPEntity (if using Windows device enumeration). Debug level could log each attempt: Probing COM5 no response., COM6 device found \[ID]. This granularity helps when troubleshooting why a device wasnt found (maybe it was on COM7 but an error occurred). In the earlier code example, we showed how each port attempt could be logged at Debug and the summary at Info. Thats a good pattern to follow. The current implementation with `Console.WriteLine` likely printed something for each device found  that should be replaced with proper logger calls as demonstrated.

**Performance-sensitive scenarios:** USB communication can be performance-sensitive (if streaming data). Some tips:

*   **Batch logging:** If your SDK reads data in a tight loop, dont log inside each iteration by default. If needed, accumulate stats and log occasionally. For example, rather than logging each of 1000 GPS NMEA sentences received per minute, perhaps log Received 1000 messages in last minute, 2 checksum errors every minute (Info), with the ability to enable trace to see individual messages if diagnosing a specific issue.
*   **Use appropriate log levels:** Make the default (Info) level logs succinct and not too frequent. Put chattier stuff in Debug/Trace. So in production, if someone enables Info or Warning they get a manageable stream of key events, not a firehose.
*   **Asynchronous logging considerations:** The act of logging itself is usually fast, but if you do an extremely high volume, consider that logging frameworks might buffer or have some overhead. Microsofts logger is quite fast, but if you truly hit performance issues, you could use techniques like dedicating a background task to logging or using EventSource as mentioned. In most SDK scenarios, this wont be necessary unless you are logging megabytes of data.

**Distinguish developer debug vs end-user info:** In device communication libraries, sometimes theres a split between logs meant for the developer of the software (to debug integration issues) versus logs that might be exposed to an end-user or administrator. For example, an end-user might want logs that say Device connected/disconnected or Error: device not responding, but not the raw hex dumps. Meanwhile, as a developer, during integration or troubleshooting, you want *everything*. The solution is the log level separation. Encourage application developers to run at Info or Warn for normal operation (which would give high-level events and errors), and use Debug/Trace when they need to investigate deeper issues with the SDK.

**Test your logging under real conditions:** Its a good idea to test how your SDK behaves with logging turned on at high verbosity in a stress scenario. Does it keep up? Does it alter timing (e.g., if writing logs slows down reads)? For a USB SDK, if debug logging is too slow, it might actually affect timing-sensitive communication. If you find that, then you should emphasize EventSource or such which can handle high volume better, or document that high verbosity is only for testing. Also ensure that turning logs off truly eliminates the overhead (use `IsEnabled` guards or source generators for heavy spots as needed).

**Example of logging strategy for a read loop:**

```csharp
public byte[] ReadPacket()
{
    // ... reading logic
    if(success) {
        if(_logger.IsEnabled(LogLevel.Trace)) {
            _logger.LogTrace("RECV {Length} bytes: {Bytes}", packet.Length, BitConverter.ToString(packet));
        }
        return packet;
    } else {
        _logger.LogWarning("Timed out waiting for packet (after {Timeout}ms)", _readTimeout);
        throw new TimeoutException($"No packet received in {_readTimeout}ms");
    }
}
```

In this pseudo-code: on success, it logs the data at Trace (very verbose) level. On timeout, it logs a warning and throws an exception. The use of `IsEnabled(LogLevel.Trace)` ensures we only format the bytes to a hex string if trace logging is actually on.

**System.IO.Ports as a comparison:** The built-in `System.IO.Ports.SerialPort` class in .NET doesn't actually do any logging  its a fairly old-style API. It reports errors via exceptions (e.g., `IOException` on some failures) or events (`ErrorReceived` event). Its essentially silent unless an error occurs. That reinforces the idea: **your library should function correctly without requiring logs**; logs are an add-on for insight. System.IO.Ports not having logging means developers often had to add their own instrumentation around it to debug issues. By providing logging in your SDK, youre giving a better dev experience. But you still follow the same model: use exceptions/events for actual error handling and state changes, and use logs for additional detail.

## 6. Real-World Examples & Patterns

Lets briefly survey how some well-known .NET libraries and frameworks handle logging and errors, to reinforce the guidance with concrete cases:

*   **Entity Framework Core (EF Core):** EF Core uses `Microsoft.Extensions.Logging` for its internal logs. In fact, if you use EF Core in an ASP.NET Core app, it automatically picks up the apps logger and will emit logs for things like executed SQL commands, transaction rollbacks, etc. By default, in production, only warnings or errors from EF are logged (to avoid overhead), but you can configure it. EF Core defines event IDs for its logs and uses structured logging (parameters in SQL commands are logged separately from the query template, etc.). Its a good example of a library using ILogger abstraction *without requiring the user to do anything special*   its integrated via DI when available. EF Core also has alternate mechanisms (like interceptors and diagnostic listeners) for advanced scenarios, but for most cases, hooking into ILogger is sufficient for logging. In terms of errors, EF throws exceptions like `DbUpdateException`, `DbUpdateConcurrencyException`, etc., which are custom exceptions carrying info (like entries that failed)  demonstrating custom exceptions for domain-specific issues (e.g., a concurrency token mismatch). It uses standard exceptions for common things (ArgumentException for bad arguments, InvalidOperationException for misuses, etc.). [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/ef/core/logging-events-diagnostics/), [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/ef/core/logging-events-diagnostics/)

*   **Azure SDK (e.g., Azure.Storage, Azure.EventHubs, etc.):** As discussed, Azure client libraries use EventSource for logging. They do not expose `ILogger` in their public API at all. Instead, they let you enable logging by using their `AzureEventSourceListener` helper. For instance, to see Azure SDK logs you might write: `new AzureEventSourceListener((e, message) => Console.WriteLine(message), EventLevel.Informational)`. Under the hood, Azure libraries have an internal EventSource (usually named after the package, like `Azure-Core` or `Azure-Storage-Blobs`). They log request details, retries, etc., to that. One reason they chose EventSource is consistency and performance; they have many SDKs in many languages, and wanted a uniform approach. They also throw exceptions (usually a common `RequestFailedException` for service call failures, which includes the HTTP status, error code, and message) to signal errors to the user. Notably, Azure SDKs guidance says: *Only log information that is not possible to determine from the exception.*. This is a great guiding principle: e.g., they log the outgoing request and response *because* if an operation fails, the exception will tell you it failed and maybe an error code, but it wont show the full request detail. So logs supplement exceptions. We can adopt similar thinking: log the things that an exception alone wouldnt convey. For example, if a read times out, the TimeoutException tells you it timed out, but maybe a log can tell you timed out after 3 attempts or timed out waiting for ACK frame which gives more context.

*   **ASP.NET Core / Generic Host:** While not an SDK, its worth noting the *pattern* used by the Generic Host and ASP.NET for logging: they set up an `ILoggerFactory` at startup (configured by appsettings or code) and then everything  including libraries  that use ILogger will funnel into it. They also register many things by default: Console and Debug providers, etc., and also an **EventSource provider** (`EventSourceLoggerProvider`) that forwards logs to EventSource (under the name "Microsoft-Extensions-Logging"). This means if someone wants to capture all logs via ETW, they can listen to that EventSource. The takeaway for you as a library author: by using ILogger, your logs automatically integrate with these systems. If someone is running your SDK in a service with structured logging to Seq/Elastic, your logs show up there with category `YourSdkName.ClassName` that they can filter. If performance is a concern, they might instead enable the EventSource provider which will collect logs via ETW (some orgs do that for minimal overhead in prod). So the ecosystem is set up to accommodate either scenario  you just need to use the hooks (ILogger or EventSource). No need for a custom global log singleton or static log level flags  stick to the patterns.

*   **Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting logging patterns:** They demonstrate good config control  e.g., in appsettings.json one can set:
    ```json
    "Logging": {
      "LogLevel": {
        "Default": "Information",
        "Contoso.UsbSdk": "Debug",
        "Microsoft": "Warning"
      }
    }
    ```
    This would turn on Debug for your SDKs namespace while keeping most other stuff at Info or higher. This is exactly why using category (via ILogger<T>) is powerful. Encourage users (via documentation) to utilize such config to get the desired verbosity for your SDK. Also, the Generic Host attaches an `ILoggerProvider` for EventLogs when running as a Windows service, etc., so by using ILogger you inherit all those sinks. In summary, your librarys logs can go wherever the host environment deems appropriate, just by conforming to the standard interfaces.

*   **System.IO.Ports (legacy):** As mentioned, it doesnt log. It throws exceptions (like `IOException` for failure to open a port, `TimeoutException` if a read timeout is set and expires). It also has events like `DataReceived`, `ErrorReceived` to inform about some issues (the `ErrorReceived` event can indicate parity errors, overrun errors from the serial driver). In modern .NET, if we were designing it anew, we might instead have it accept an ILogger for parity error notifications rather than an event  but events were the chosen approach at the time. For your SDK, prefer logging for things that dont require an immediate application reaction (e.g., we had a parity error but we retried and recovered could be a log). If something truly needs app action, maybe an event or callback  but thats more an API design question beyond logging scope.

## 7. Configuration & Control of Logging in Your SDK

Finally, consider how the **consumer** of your SDK will configure and control the logging and error behaviors:

*   **Exposing Logging Configuration:** Ideally, you shouldnt need to expose much beyond accepting a logger. The application will configure the loggers level and output. Document how to enable logging for your SDK (like pass an ILoggerFactory to the constructor or the SDK will use any ILoggerFactory provided through dependency injection). If using EventSource, document how to capture those events (e.g., on Windows, use PerfMon or logman; or use our provided helper to print to console). Some libraries provide a simple toggle, e.g., `SdkDiagnostics.LogLevel = LogLevel.Debug` that internally sets up a console listener. This can be convenient for quick use (like, call `UsbSdk.EnableLogging(LogLevel.Information)` to quickly get console logs during dev). If you add such shortcuts, implement them by tying into the standard methods (for example, create a ConsoleLogger via LoggerFactory, or create an EventListener) rather than reinventing logging.

*   **Runtime log level control:** If using ILogger, the app can change the log level anytime (for example, if using appsettings with reload-on-change, or programmatically via filtering). Your SDK doesnt need to manage that  just check `IsEnabled` if doing expensive work. If using EventSource, the level is controlled by the listener enabling events at certain levels. You could also allow switching on verbose mode in code by instantiating an `EventListener`. The key is, any changes to logging level should propagate to your library naturally. Test that turning the log level to Debug indeed causes your debug logs to appear, etc.

*   **Conditional compilation flags:** To reiterate, you generally wouldnt require consumers to compile your library differently for more logging. Thats more for your internal builds. Use runtime control for consumers.

*   **Log Filtering & Categorization:** We covered this, but to summarize: ensure each log message has a clear category (which ILogger<T> handles) and maybe an event ID. For example, define a static class of event IDs if you want, like `public static EventId DeviceFoundEvent = new EventId(100, "DeviceFound")`. Then when logging, `_logger.LogInformation(DeviceFoundEvent, "Device {Device} found", dev)`. This allows filtering by event ID too. Not required, but could be nice if your logs are numerous, so users can easily filter e.g., all discovery-related logs (by a range of IDs or by text).

*   **Telemetry and metrics:** If needed, think about exposing metrics such as bytes transmitted or error count. This could be via logs (aggregate and log out stats) or via EventCounters (EventSource has an `EventCounter` API to produce counters that can be tracked, e.g., a counter for BytesPerSecond). If your library will be used in large applications, these telemetry points can be helpful. For instance, define an `EventCounter` for throughput or latency. This might be overkill initially, but its something to note under telemetry. A lightweight approach is simply to log summary info occasionally as mentioned.

*   **Testing error handling:** Provide recommendations to users on how to test or simulate errors (maybe a debug mode that intentionally triggers a retry scenario, etc.). This helps them see that your logging and exceptions work as expected. For example, if theres a way to run the SDK against a dummy device or simulator, the user can observe logs for normal vs error flows.

Lastly, keep performance in mind in all these features. Enabling extensive logging should not drastically degrade the librarys primary function (unless explicitly documented that it will). Using the techniques above  source generators, IsEnabled checks, EventSource  will ensure that when logging is off, your SDK runs at full speed.
